    "), the same classic solution can be applied to the use of LLMs for simulating human responses.",
    "One implication is that we simply cannot avoid running our experiment or survey on at least some sample of real human subjects.",
    "Notice that the value of the LLM itself will then depend on the nature of the research application.",
    "Some economics experiments are about testing anomalies, or even a single anomaly (for example the Allais Paradox).",
    "In that case the research context Q(•) might contain as few as one design r, and the economic concept V r we wish the LLM to be able to reproduce is the minimum number of human subject responses we think we would need for a reliable answer to \"how do people tend to choose given this menu of options r?\""
  ],
